European inflation on food slipped away
The accelerating inflation in the euro area is mainly due to fast-moving increases in food prices.
The price increase in November was higher than expected in the 13 countries of the eurozone, with annual inflation of 3.1 per cent, after 2.6 per cent in October, the EU’s Luxembourg statistical office reported.
The official prediction was only 3% likely, Bloomberg said.
Unlike the central banks of the United States, the United Kingdom and Canada, the European Central Bank (ECB) has not cut the base rate, saying that a reduction along with rising commodity prices and decreasing unemployment would lead to a spiral of inflation.
The ECB wants to keep the inflation rate below, but close to, 2%.
According to one analyst, the ECB is in the trap of twenty-two: “you have to talk down” inflation so that it doesn’t have to act on this later.
In Germany, November inflation is at 3.3 percent, a 12-year record; in Spain, it has risen to 4.1 from 3.6.
Eurozone inflation has been driven high by rising food and energy prices.
Wheat futures rose by 88 percent and soybean prices reached their highest level since 1973.
Food oil and dairy products also had to be paid significantly higher in 2007.
The world price of oil rose by 52 percent this year, and last month it cost almost <0x24>100 a barrel of black gold.
According to the ECB, inflation will jump from 2.1 per cent this year to 2.5 per cent in 2008, but will drop to 1.9 per cent in 2009.
Analysts say the 12-month inflation rate will remain around 3% for the next 3-4 months, but the annual average rate will be 2.1 percent.
At the same time, it is expected that the ECB will have reduced interest rates twice in 2008.
