The most expensive is Auchan, with Tesco raising nearly a fifth.
In the trade triangle in Budaörs, hypermarkets maintained last year’s average price increase of 16 percent, with the difference that VAT did not increase this year.
Article of the Daily Economy
The average increase of the Daily Christmas Basket in the Budaörs trading triangle was 16% this year, but in all hypermarkets there was an increase of well over a thousand forints in value.
As prices in grocery stores have already “shrunk” in December last year, there has been no significant increase in prices compared to the previous high base.
But it is obviously frightening for consumers that what they could get last year for well over nine thousand forints, they can’t get it for even ten thousand for now.
The Daily basket exceeded the psychological limit of 10,000 forints by at least 91 forints in the hypermarkets examined.
The highest basket value was 10 573 forints.
(In 2003, the basket cost 6800 HUF.)
The price of Unicum and live fish remained almost at last year’s level, but turkey breast fillet, walnuts and poppy also became very expensive.
The price of flour and bread in the stores followed the data of the HCSO, although we found a kilogram of bread in Auchan for 139 forints.
The competition did not push the price of the product below 200 forints.
It was also surprising in this shop that the price of the two-liter reversible bottle of Coca-Cola was under 200 forints, so even with the deposit fee, only 257 forints were requested for the product.
However, this year Auchan was the most expensive in the Daily basket, while Cora was the cheapest.
Compared to last year’s Christmas prices, Cora and Tesco have increased their daily shopping cart prices by about 18 to 18 percent.
Compared to last year’s most expensive and this year’s cheapest basket value, the difference was 12%, while the difference between last year’s cheapest and this year’s most expensive basket value was 21%.
The average increment was 1,480 in HUF.
Last year, the average price increase was HUF 1,206, so last Christmas the VAT increase had an impact on prices.
It was precisely this process that disrupted trade, and the stores were apparently unable to decide what margins to apply for each product, because they were unable to calculate the impact of price changes on consumption.
(If the turnover of a product is badly planned by the trader, it can make a significant profit on the margin adjusted for the traffic intensity.)
Due to the VAT, last year the price increase of the Daily Basket was so extreme that the most expensive was HUF 1,720 more than in 2006, while the price difference for the cheapest was only HUF 844.
This year this extreme did not show up, as the most expensive one was HUF 1630 more than last year, and the cheapest one was HUF 1284 more expensive.
Compared to the two Christmas seasons, there was a catastrophic increase in prices, with daily consumer goods in hypermarkets rising by more than 30 percent in less than 20 months.
(This, by the way, does not necessarily justify the data of the Central Statistical Office: for some basic foods, the statistical office measured a price increase of more than 30 percent over a 12-month period.
In addition to eggs, for example.)
According to the Daily Basket, this seems almost impossible for the latter, as the price level of the already quite expensive product last year produced a price increase of just over 10 percent compared to the base in the worst case scenario.
The flour suppliers seem to be in a stronger position than the egg suppliers, and the drastic price rises have been scammed by the multinationals as well.
In the trading golden triangle, hypers do not complain, constantly reporting a good year.
In our experience, most of the customers in the three stores we visited are no longer interested in prices.
They buy a lot of everything, they take the durable food to the plateau.
On Wednesday morning, there were serious lines in front of the cash registers in all three stores, because the number of visitors suddenly increased.
However, we know that in rural areas the turnover is weaker, and more people complain to research companies that even their plans do not generate revenue, not only in the case of food, but also in the case of durable consumer goods.
They save on disinfectants in many places
This year, more than a thousand infections have been registered in hospitals, mainly due to improper use of antibiotics.
The hygienic conditions of hospitals, the overcrowding of the beds and the overcrowding of the staff are not in favor of stopping infections, says the head of the department of the National Centre for Epidemiology.
They also save on disinfectants in many places.
Recently, MRSA infection was diagnosed in the traumatology department of J<0xC3><0xA1>nos Hospital.
A man was found to be resistant to antibiotics after a serious accident.
The patient was isolated.
A similar infection occurred earlier this year.
The victim of a serious car accident was released from the hospital, but soon after he had to return with MRSA, and a major surgery had not been performed since because of the bacteria in his body.
Until 10 December of this year, 1,094 hospital infections caused by multi-resistant pathogens were reported to the National Nosocomial Surveillance System, said Karolina Böröcz, head of department at the National Centre for Epidemiology.
This means that so many infections caused by multi-resistant pathogens have certainly been registered in hospitals, the rest is unknown.
About two-thirds (683 infections) of the infections were caused by MRSA, a drug known as methicillin-oxacillin-resistant Staphylococcus aureus.
A third of people carry Staphylococcus aureus (SA) in their noses without causing the disease.
Infections caused by SA (e.g. pharyngitis, tonsillitis, skin infections, wound infection) respond well to antibiotics and are well curable.
However, if antibiotics are used too much or not properly, a bacterium that responds well to antibiotics develops into a bacterium that is highly resistant to antibiotics and spreads rapidly in poor hospital conditions.
Especially when the immune system is temporarily or permanently malfunctioning, it can cause serious hospital infections such as wound infection or blood poisoning - sepsis - in patients with a weakened body, elderly or low weight.
According to the medical director of J<0xC3><0xA1>nos Hospital, there is nothing special about MRSA infection, such infections belong to the daily practice of hospitals.
The infection should not be confused with the epidemic, MRSA is just not there, said Tibor Nyulasi, where the presence of the pathogen is not tested.
Resistant to antibiotics
"Such patients are isolated, the nursing staff treats the patient with rubber gloves and masks, and they have the appropriate antibiotics to treat them," said Tibor Nyulasi.
Patients admitted to the hospital will be checked in advance for MRSA, but it is not always possible to avoid infection.
Not in fashion for sampling
The vast majority of hospital infections caused by MRSA could be prevented, but the current hospital conditions and conditions in Hungary are not favourable for preventing the development and spread of multi-resistant pathogens, says Karolina Böröcz.
Since this infection typically occurs in hospitals and nursing homes, hospitals should check incoming patients and immediately isolate patients carrying MRSA.
However, microbiological sampling is not fashionable in Hungarian hospitals.
The fact that the National Health Insurance Fund does not fund these tests also plays a role.
Most cases are thus revealed when the patient has a detectable MRSA infection, said the head of the epidemiological center.
The European Union has strict recommendations for the proper use of antibiotics in human medicine, and there are also domestic guidelines for the treatment of certain infections and pathologies.
Antibiotic therapy should be targeted, i.e. microbiological tests should be carried out to prevent the development of resistance to medicines, but hospitals do not always adhere to this.
Microbiological samples are even rarer in outpatient and primary care, Böröcz Karolina said.
They save on disinfectants
Scientific evidence confirms that MRSA is most commonly transmitted from one patient to another through the mediation of healthcare personnel.
Therefore, hand washing, the use of gloves, masks play a very important role, but there are also significant shortcomings in this in hospitals.
MRSA is transmitted by droplets and contact, however, in the domestic hospital conditions it is not always possible to isolate the infected patient.
In fact, the wards are often crowded, and the beds are often very close to each other, although, from an epidemiological point of view, patients should be at least 1.5 meters apart.
Unfortunately, Karolina Böröcz also noted that hospitals in poor financial situation are saving on disinfectants, there are few nurses and many patients, so the chances of developing infections are even higher.
According to Karolina Böröcz, where the appropriate precautions are followed, there are fewer such infections, or the spread of the pathogen can be stopped.
Government program against MRSA
Treatment of MRSA infection is a huge expense for health insurers, so they are fighting it everywhere.
In England, for example, the government has included prevention and reduction of MRSA in its programme.
The program seems to be successful, and the reported data show a decreasing trend of MRSA infections in England.
The European Centre for Disease Prevention (ECDC) focuses on preventing the development of multi-resistant pathogens (including MRSA) and hospital infections caused by such pathogens.
