Political Capital: The Hungarian Guard increased the risk of the country
The activities of the Hungarian Guard, founded in August this year with the support of the Jobbik Movement for Hungary, have increased the political risk of Hungary and the region in several respects, according to the Political Capital Risk Analysis Division.
The company’s “risk warning” stated that the biggest political risk in connection with the activities of the Hungarian Guard is that “with the already existing ethnic tension between the Hungarian Gypsies and non-Gypsies, violent ethnic clashes may develop even in the short term”.
The main reason for this is that the political strategy of the Hungarian Guard is probably aimed at provoking such an act, the research institute added.
This is due to one of the main omissions of Hungarian political actors: “the public discussion of the Roma issue was handed over by public actors to representatives of radical and extremist political groups who could build a political strategy against the Gypsy-Hungarian opposition.”
This deepens the problem, makes normal dialogue impossible, strengthens extremists, and increases the likelihood of violent conflicts, they believe.
In addition, according to the research institute, the activities of the Hungarian Guard have “deteriorated significantly the image of Hungary abroad, especially with regard to the confidence in the stability and democratic development of the country”.
It is a part of the reorganisation of radical and far-right groups in Hungary, which has gained more and more publicity and momentum since the autumn of 2006, that since the summer of 2007 several organisations have been formed in Hungary, calling themselves “national self-defence” associations.
“The common feature of these groups is that they define themselves as NGOs, while openly proclaiming the preparation of their members – even armed – for defence (disaster protection, defence, law enforcement) tasks, citing the incompetence of the police, the army, or the state,” they added.
They noted that all this is done in accordance with the method which, based on the anti-political and anti-partisan nature of society, seeks to put various political aspirations into civilian robes.
The emphasis on civility and the form of the association is therefore not only intended to avoid the legal pitfalls of court registration in the case of these associations, but is also a political strategy.
According to the analysis, the activity of the Hungarian Guard is also a risk-increasing factor in terms of neighbourly relations.
“In recent months, the Hungarian Guard has been referred to as a potential threat in several neighbouring countries, and the ultra-nationalist political actors in some neighbouring countries want to justify their own anti-Hungarian policy by citing the formation of the Hungarian Guard.
This has an impact on the political stability of the region,” they added.
