The holidays are not red everywhere.
In Hungary, the law clearly identifies red-letter days, and it has become common practice to rearrange workdays around the holidays, which will be less next year.
The holidays are not unified in the EU and the United States.
The Hungarian legal system distinguishes between national and state holidays and public holidays.
The public holidays are mostly linked to church holidays and important historical events.
We are celebrating the New Year as well: the last day of the Old Year and the first day of the New Year are both holidays – the latter for the sole purpose of resting the New Year’s Eve.
We have a total of 11 red-letter holidays throughout the year.
The 15th of March and the 23rd of October, commemorating the Revolution of 1848, are also national holidays.
On the 20th of August we celebrate the founding of the state, on the 1st of May we celebrate the work, and on the 1st and 2nd of November we commemorate our deceased relatives and friends.
In addition, we have a two-day holiday of Easter, Pentecost and Christmas.
Since our state, national, or even religious holidays are seldom on weekends according to the calendar, it has become a practice to shift workdays when we work only one day before or after the red-letter holiday.
It is true that the price of extended weekends is that we do not stay away from work and school on the preceding Saturdays.
The exact time of the day immediately before or after the holiday is regulated by a special decree of the Minister of Labour for many years.
The legislation applies to all employers and their employees, civil servants and public service employees.
However, it does not affect service companies and institutions that operate without interruption and, due to their purpose, also operate on public holidays.
This year, the work schedule changes only around the end of the year holidays: from 24 December life in the country almost stops, as experience shows that most people “slide off” the days between Christmas and New Year’s Eve, or use their saved holidays for this purpose.
Next year, there will be more of our holidays in the middle of the week and at the end of the week, so there will be fewer shifts of working days than this year.
First, the calendar changes around the holiday of work, so that the workers can stay at home for four days.
Saturday, April 26, will be a working day in exchange for Friday, May 2.
The second relocation is linked to the 23 October holiday: work will have to be done on Saturday, 18 October, instead of the 24th on Friday.
However, the end of the year can be completely in the spirit of the holiday next year, as from 24 December there will be a non-stop break almost everywhere, even if it falls on New Year’s Eve Wednesday.
