After more than 60 years of encryption, the Bad Arolsen archive became public, documenting the fate of 17 and a half million victims of the Hitler regime.
The 47 million archive documents, which occupy 27 kilometers of shelving in Bad Arolsen in the province of Hessen, have so far been searchable only for “humanitarian” purposes, providing unique and name-based insights for former victims or their descendants.
Eleven states, including Germany, France, Israel and the United States, agreed to open the archive for researchers and historians in May 2006.
After all the states ratified the treaty, the archive was opened yesterday.
Confidential information
The opening of the archives in Bad Arolsen will allow historians to conduct research on “the relocation of prisoners, camp residents and the health of forced laborers,” explains Reto Meistern, director of the archives managed by the International Committee of the Red Cross.
Until now, several states, including Germany, have opposed the disclosure of the documents because they contain names and thus confidential information.
For example, some deportees may have alleged homosexuality or mental disabilities.
The lists of concentration camps and the arrest warrants issued by the Gestapo began to be collected after the war for practical reasons, with the aim of locating civilians who were deported or sentenced to forced labour, and possibly providing evidence of their internment, on the basis of which they could receive compensation.
Currently, more than 300 permanent employees in Bad Arolsen are processing tens of thousands of unique needs.
However, some scholars do not consider the opening of the Bad Arolsen archive of paramount importance.
"These documents are basically nothing new," said Professor Wolfgang Benz, director of the Anti-Semitism Research Center at the Berlin University of Technology in 2006.
