Congress approves takeover of MiFID that entered into force on November 1
In parallel with the parliamentary process, which ended today with a congressional vote approving the Senate amendments, the government initiated a social dialogue on the legislation underpinning the law so that both could come into force before the end of the year.
The representatives of the various groups unanimously underlined the efforts of the MPs and senators in negotiations and agreements aimed at developing the most favourable normatives to protect investors, as well as the detailed regulation of the activities of the companies, in order to operate effectively in the market.
Mifid, which amends the Securities Markets Act, will enable the modernisation of financial markets while strengthening investor protection, expanding the supervisory powers of the Spanish National Securities Markets Commission (CNMV) and promoting cooperation between different supervisors in the European Union.
The new directive will enable financial advisory services to be provided to specialised companies, but also to natural or legal persons, as well as to securities distribution companies, securities agencies and portfolio management companies, by creating a new form of financial services company (ESIS), namely financial advisory companies (AFIs).
In addition, the law will increase the number of systems capable of carrying out operations involving funds, thereby adding to the regulated secondary markets the multilateral trading platforms and internalisation systems for the execution of orders, which will compete with current stock market participants.
In addition, the Act requires investment firms to provide market information on the defining aspects of their business profile, their risk-taking and risk-management methods, and to keep records of all operations carried out in order to facilitate the control of CNMV.
A number of amendments have been introduced by the Congressional Economic Commission. Of these, it is of paramount importance that securitised debts are treated as "complex" funds due to the high risk they pose to the investor. This has been proven in the context of the US high-risk mortgage lending (subprime).
On the other hand, the transposition of the directive was also used to legally outline the scope of activity of those with economic and entrepreneurial qualifications, 30 years after the Royal Decree, which defined the professional functions that could be carried out only by economists, came into force in 1977.
The Senate, in turn, proposed the creation of new actors in the financial sector, such as an agent for an intermediary who works for someone else’s account, does not need permission from CNMV, and can market products or acquire clients for several investment companies at the same time.
