What kind of insurance is right for me?
Car insurance, which means safety for the owner of the car in the face of various damage events, entails significant costs and depends on a number of factors, such as age, gender, date of obtaining the driving licence, marital status, type of car to be insured and type of use.
Buying a car is just the first step.
In fact, choosing the right insurance is often more difficult than deciding what kind of car you want.
First of all, we need to be clear about what this is about.
Car insurance is an agreement between the insurance company and the insurer.
This agreement takes the form of an insurance contract, which states that the insurance company undertakes compensation for the fixed premium in the event of an incident.
In practice, the premium is the amount paid for insurance, which is determined by taking into account various factors such as age, gender, date of obtaining a driving licence, marital status, type of car to be insured, its use, and more.
Insurance companies determine the insurance premium on the basis of statistics, i.e. a higher amount is paid by the person who represents a higher risk of accidents.
That’s why people over the age of 25 or women pay less because, according to statistics, they’re less risky because they’re more cautious.
Similarly, according to the reports, insurance companies concluded that married people cause fewer accidents than lonely people.
The frequency of use of the car is decisive.
With more frequent use, the chance of an accident increases.
When determining the premium, insurance companies take into account a number of factors.
Therefore, the owner should carefully look into it so that he can choose the most suitable form of insurance for his profile.
In the following, we present the most important factors for choosing, so that we can best adapt to the insurer’s needs and create an acceptable price.
When concluding an insurance contract, people under the age of 25 face a number of disadvantages, such as lack of driving experience and the freshness of their driving license.
Although it is ideal to be insured against all dangers, there are also more economical solutions.
More cautious drivers can take out complete insurance on their own, so they can be insured against all dangers and the price will be affordable.
In this type of contract, the insured pays part of the damage.
"The amount of the self-contributor to the insurer depends on the insurance premium; the higher the premium, the lower the self-contributor," says Luis Noguera, head of First Europe's online insurance intermediary in Spain.
Another option is extended third-party liability insurance, where the customer insures himself against damage to others, but not against damage to his own car.
In addition, it will be insured against theft, fire damage and loss of the car.
A word of advice.
If you are under the age of 25, be careful and avoid accidents as this will affect the bonus and reduce the amount you will have to pay in the future.
A bonus is a discount on the basic rate of the insurance company.
The penalty charged in relation to the basic tariff is called a malus.
“The amount of the bonus and the amount of the bonus depends on the insurance company and its profits.
If the company has had a good year, it can afford to raise the bonus,” Noguera explains.
If the age of 25 has already been exceeded, it is easier for owners to take out adequate insurance, as the risk of accidents decreases due to the experience gained over the years.
We recommend that you take out full insurance.
"Usually, young people are not yet able to apply their experience to accidents, or even to driving," says the director of the European Insurance Company in Spain, adding that the majority of accidents occur in the second year of driving, when drivers have already overcome the fear of a beginner.
If the insured person is already married but has no children, it is best to take out full insurance, of course, if your financial possibilities allow.
Insurance companies consider married couples with children to be the least risky clients, so the premium is also lower in their case.
In this case, it is best to have full insurance on your own (it can reach 300 euros), or if they have a higher bonus, they can extend the insurance from the third year of the vehicle to cover the damage caused to someone else.
“They drive more calmly, but at the same time they have more purchasing power and can afford to have a higher share,” Noguera said.
In the case of pensioners, we recommend the full insurance on own account (which is around 150 euros), or in case of a higher bonus, it can be extended to liability insurance.
Car insurance is very important, not only because it provides protection to the owner in the event of damage events, but also because it is a large expense, so it is essential to choose the personalized form of insurance appropriately.
