Other fears about the Russian-Ukrainian gas dispute
There has been a renewed gas dispute between Ukraine and Russia, which could also affect Russian fuel to be shipped to Western Europe.
Most of the Russian gas exported to the European Union (EU) is flown through Ukraine and disputes between the two nations are always attentive.
Kiev has said that if Moscow raises the price of gas to be paid by the Ukrainians, they will also impose higher transit costs on Russia.
As a result of a previous dispute between the two countries last year, supplies to EU countries have decreased.
The latest dispute between Kiev and Moscow concerns an attempt by the Ukrainian government and the Russian state-owned gas monopoly Gazprom to agree on the price of gas to be paid by Ukraine to Russia in 2008.
Gazprom said it would have to increase its gas production from neighbouring Turkmenistan by 50% compared to the price agreement concluded with Ukraine in 2008.
According to analysts, this could mean a 40% increase in the price of a shipment from Gazprom for Ukraine.
"It is important that during the negotiations we argue in line with one of the most important transit countries for natural gas," Ukrainian Economy Minister Anatoly Kinah told Reuters.
“The changes in gas prices should definitely be linked to our debate on the cost of transits through Ukraine (and to Western Europe).
As a result of the recent major gas dispute between Moscow and Kiev, Gazprom shut down the gas tap leading to Ukraine in January 2006.
This resulted in a domino-like decline in exports to Western Europe, which also pushed up prices to a large extent.
A quarter of the European Union’s gas supply comes from Russian gas.
Russia has the largest natural gas reserves in the world, but most of them are still unexplored.
As a result, Gazprom will supplement its own gas supply with natural gas from Turkmenistan and other former Soviet states in Central Asia.
NHS 'must check foreign workers'
Scottish NHS committees need to improve the monitoring of criminal records of workers coming from outside Europe, a supervisory body said.
The proposal was presented by Robert Black, the chief accountant, after a doctor with a foreign nationality in Scotland was linked to the attack on Glasgow Airport in June.
Black also expressed concern that NHS Scotland does not have accurate data on its overseas workforce.
However, in its report, through a sample of five health authorities, it also pointed out key controls that were properly carried out.
Following the attack on Glasgow Airport, the chief accountant checked the list of employees recruited outside the European Economic Area.
Bilal Abdullaho, a 28-year-old Iraqi doctor at Royal Alexandra Hospital in Paisley, was arrested at the airport after a jeep hit the main terminal of the building.
Abdullah was one of three doctors interviewed by the Old Bailey Court in October on charges of attempted car bombings in the UK.
The NHS committees must verify the qualifications and work experience of their employees from overseas before starting employment, as well as their availability of the necessary permits to work in the United Kingdom.
Although Scottish health committees use Disclosure Scotland to verify criminal records, the agency is not entitled to obtain such information from outside the UK.
Among other things, the Chief Auditor’s report suggested that committees should introduce a Criminal Records Office guide that would facilitate the employer’s control processes with the various overseas countries.
"While we found evidence of such checks in the personnel records, they are not being carried out regularly," the report said.
According to Black, the Scottish NHS is fulfilling its own pre-employment screening process at a high level, he added: “Our report highlights areas of the system that can be improved in order to keep up-to-date on the number of NHS overseas personnel.”
Dr. Peter Terry, president of BMA Scotland, said it was “extremely improbable” that pre-employment checks could identify potential NHS employees who could commit terrorist acts in the future.
“The report says the current pre-employment checks are working well in NHS Scotland, and the value of the proposals is not yet transparent,” he added.
According to the Scottish health authorities, the current number of overseas employees, consisting of a majority of doctors and nurses, is 1,161.
However, the chief accountant pointed out that the figures are likely to be higher, partly due to the fact that committees have problems identifying employees on indefinite leave.
The investigation also showed that the control procedures put in place by the NHS authorities in Ayrshire and Arran, Grampian, Greater Glasgow and Clyde, Lanarkshire and Lothian are largely harmonised.
These procedures covered the verification of passports, work permits and evidence of qualifications.
The Scottish Government is currently reviewing the directive and guidance on pre-employment checks for NHS staff from overseas.
Health Secretary Nicola Sturgeon said: "I am delighted that this task has been carried out following the attack on Glasgow Airport.
He also added that the Scottish Government, in cooperation with health committees, will take into account the suggestions contained in the report and will ensure that the up-to-date guidance on pre-employment inspections for all staff, including those from overseas, reflects best practice. The updated version is planned to be published next month.
