Venus is the devil twin of the Earth.
Despite the harsh atmosphere of Venus, it is more similar to Earth than previously assumed: in its atmosphere, the European space probe Venus Express has discovered lightning and in its poles wind turbulences such as those that occur on Earth in winter.
For nearly three decades, scientists have been assuming lightning on Venus.
The European space probe "Venus Express" has provided evidence - it has discovered electromagnetic waves on the edge of the atmosphere: Lightning on Venus is spreading from cloud to cloud at an altitude of about 56 kilometers, reports Christpher Russell of the University of California in Los Angeles, California, in the columns of the science magazine "Nature".
According to the famous "primordial soup theory, the formation of life on Earth was triggered by lightning: According to the theory, thunderstorms triggered reactions in the ocean that led to the formation of amino acids, the building blocks of life.
Not so on Venus: “If life ever existed there, it must have been in very early times,” explains Sean Solomon of the Carnegie Institute in Washington.
At present, there can hardly be a living organism on the surface of Venus: The atmosphere is about a hundred times denser than on Earth, and temperatures sometimes reach 500 degrees.
"Venus may be the hellish twin brother of Earth, but it's still his twin brother," Russell said.
The main question of the Esa mission is why Venus, in its mass and size so similar to Earth, is on a completely different evolutionary path.
The launch of "Venus Express" in November 2005 was a milestone in Venus research, because since the early 1990s, no probe has been on the way specifically to find this planet.
The latest findings, already presented in several "Nature" papers, do not just prove the uniqueness of Venus in the Solar System.
"They also indicate that the similarity of the neighboring planet to Earth is greater than we initially assumed," Esa said.
In addition to the already known Arctic hurricane, the researchers also discovered an even faster-moving cloud vortex in the South Pole.
The phenomenon is reminiscent of the air currents of the Earth's winter hemispheric, according to a team led by Giuseppe Piccioni from the Italian Institute of Astrofisica Spaziale e Fisica Cosmica.
The second innermost planet in the solar system has a mass almost equal to that of Earth, and with a diameter of 12,100 kilometers, it is almost the size of Earth.
The star, also known as the Evening Star, orbits the Sun in just 225 days.
However, it rotates much slower around its own axis: a Venus day lasts 243 Earth days.
Although Venus’s surface temperature of 460 degrees Celsius, coupled with a pressure of 92 bar, hardly resembles that of Earth, scientists assume that both planets were formed under identical conditions.
Both of them had accumulated water, which remained on Earth as an ocean, until Venus went into the universe.
And while on Earth, carbon dioxide is bound in the carbonate rocks, on Venus, it forms a large part of the atmosphere.
