These aren't Warhol's crates.
Anyone who connects the concepts of Sweden and the wooden box is thinking of Ikea, not Andy Warhol.
Or is it?
Currently, wooden crates manufactured in Sweden cast a dark shadow on the list of Warhol’s works.
Most of the ninety-four "Stockholm-type" Brillo Box listed here are fake.
After the Swedish newspaper "Expressen" questioned the authenticity of Andy Warhol's 1968 Brillo Boxes, the internal investigation of the Moderna Museet in Stockholm has now come to a sobering conclusion: The six "Brillo Boxes" that were donated to Moderna Museet by Pontus Hultén in 1995 are also part of the "Brillo Boxes" on the international art market.
The prehistory is a long and complicated chain of artistic and curatorial stunts.
In 1964, Warhol created the first "Brillo Boxai" in New York - painted wooden boxes based on the red-blue-white shape of the soap powder cardboard box of "Brillo".
At an exhibition of his works at the Moderna Museet in 1968, with Warhol's consent, hundreds of Brillo boxes were exhibited: These (for cost-saving reasons) were not from Warhol, but were transported directly from the Brillo cardboard factory.
It was not about works of art, but about their templates, simple exhibits.
At the same time, Warhol gave permission in 1968 to produce some Brillo wood canes in Sweden, but they were not exhibited at the Moderna Museet.
Witnesses of the era now speak of about fifteen crates that, at the time, were authenticated as the Original-Andy-Warhol-Brillo-Box under the designation "Stockholm type" and rightfully entered art and auction history.
Some of them were auctioned for over <0x24>100,000.
The problem, however, is that the legendary museum director, Pontus Hultén, later falsely claimed that in 1968 around a hundred wooden crates were produced and exhibited in Sweden, which were then left to him by Warhol.
In fact, the 105 chests of Hultén were only produced in Malmö in 1990 for an exhibition in St. Petersburg.
At that time, Warhol had been dead for three years.
In addition to the six Brillo Boxes owned by the museum, Lars Byström, the main monument manager at Moderna Museet, examined three Swedish privately owned boxes, two of which were made in Stockholm in 1968: The pressed chipboards were first flattened and polished, and then applied the white oil paint with a brush.
The structure of the 1990 copies, on the other hand, indicates that the paint was applied directly to the chipboard with a paint roller without a foundation - and it is not oil paint, but acrylic paint.
"These boxes were not authenticated by the artist and should be removed from the official list of Andy Warhol's Brillo Boxes," says Lars Nittve, director of Moderna Museet: "Unless the New York's 'Andy Warhol Art Authentication Board' decides otherwise, Moderna Museet will include the six boxes in its collection as copies/exhibition materials."
The Authentication Board, of course, announced in June that it would investigate “serious allegations” of soap-powder crates.
Since then, however, they have been enveloped in unrelenting silence.
